cking whether \"& Coriander\" actually passes the hard filters by working through each condition—it clears the length requirement, isn't flagged as an ingredient or metadata, doesn't start with a number, and since it's two words, it bypasses the single-word checks, so it does pass.\n\nLooking at the full candidates that made it through, including the complete recipe title at 54 characters, they all pass the hard filters. But the embedding scoring returns an empty result, which suggests the threshold calculation might be filtering everything out—if the best score is around 0.09, the threshold would be set to 0.08, so I need to trace through why nothing meets that cutoff.\n\nI'm realizing the issue might be in how the lines are being joined. That long paragraph starting with \"Baked eggs is one of my all-time favourite breakfast dishes\" contains a period followed by a space and letter, which would normally trigger the filter, but it's over 80 characters so it gets excluded anyway. When I look at the actual line structure in the file, I need to check which lines are actually being considered for the multi-line join operation. Now the candidates get scored by their embedding similarity. I'm wondering why the final result could be empty—maybe the `selected` filter is too strict. If the best candidate scores around 0.15, the threshold becomes `Math.max(0.08, 0.105)` which is 0.105, so both individual lines and the joined version should pass. But then during deduplication, I realize the single-line title is actually a substring of the longer joined version, so one would get filtered out.\n\nThat would leave \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" as the result, not the full version with \"& Coriander\"—yet the actual result is empty. This makes me think the scoring might be failing entirely, or perhaps the body text contains many competing candidates that are scoring higher and drowning out the actual title lines.\n\nLet me trace through the filtering more carefully. There's a garbled text check that flags lines with periods followed by spaces and letters, unless they end in parentheses. The first line about eggs being a favorite breakfast dish is over 80 characters anyway, so it gets filtered by length. As for \"& Coriander\" on its own, that probably doesn't score well as a recipe name embedding-wise.\n\nI'm wondering if the multi-title guard might be the culprit here. Let me check what happens when multiple candidates are selected.\n\nFiltering ALL_CAPS candidates...\n\nI'm trying to trace through why \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" returns an empty string. The most likely culprits are either the hard filters rejecting the joined title, the scoring threshold being too strict, or something failing during the deduplication step.\n\nLet me verify the hard filters on this specific string: it's 54 characters so it passes the length check, it doesn't look like an ingredient measurement, doesn't start with a number, and doesn't appear to be metadata. For the garbled text check, the letter count and vowel distribution both look normal, so that shouldn't be filtering it out either.\n\nNow I'm checking the multi-word lowercase pattern—looking at whether short lowercase words appear at the start of segments. \"with\" is lowercase but has 4 letters, which exceeds the threshold for triggering that filter, and the other words are capitalized, so this passes that check too.\n\nSo the recipe title clears all the hard filters. Now I need to think about the embedding-based scoring, though without actually computing the embeddings I can only reason through what the scores might be.\n\nThe title should semantically match a recipe, so I'd expect it to score reasonably well—unless the function returns undefined when nothing hits the threshold, which would show up as an empty string in the test output. But wait, I'm looking more closely at the `buildCandidates` function and how it uses `findBurstEnd` to skip past an initial burst of short garbled lines before evaluating candidates.\n\nFor the Baked Eggs file, the first line is 42 characters long, so it doesn't trigger the garbled burst detection—`burstEnd` would be 0. That's not the issue. I'm wondering if maybe the deduplication logic is somehow preferring a shorter substring like \"& Coriander\" over the full title, though that doesn't quite make sense since the full title isn't even a substring match...\n\nActually, wait—\"& Coriander\" *is* contained in the lowercased version of \"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce & coriander\". So if both strings passed the scoring threshold, the deduplication would filter out the longer one in favor of the shorter substring. But the output is empty, which means neither string is making it through. Let me look more carefully at the deduplication filter logic to understand what's actually being removed. I'm realizing the deduplication logic should keep \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" since it's a substring of the full title, but the actual result is empty—so something else in the filtering or scoring pipeline must be eliminating it entirely.\n\nLet me reconsider what candidates are even being generated. The ingredient lines like \"4 tbsp olive oil\" get filtered out by length constraints, but others like \"5 garlic cloves, bashed and thinly sliced\" might pass through and compete in the scoring against the title itself.\n\nLooking at the filtering logic more carefully: lines starting with numbers get caught by the regex check, and short lowercase strings like \"sea salt flakes\" fail the garbled text detection. So most of the ingredient list is being eliminated. The real contenders would be longer, properly formatted lines from the instructions section—things like \"To make the sauce, preheat a saucepan...\" or \"Preheat the oven to 180°C/fan 160°C/gas mark 4...\" These might be scoring higher than the title because they contain more keyword matches.\n\nThe title itself appears to be split across two lines—\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" on one line and \"& Coriander\" on the next—which could be breaking the matching logic when it tries to reconstruct the full name. I'm realizing the algorithm is returning an empty string, which suggests the threshold is filtering out all candidates. The threshold calculation uses `Math.max(0...` and if every option scores below that cutoff, the selected list ends up empty, resulting in the empty string output. For \"Baked Eggs...\" the issue likely stems from the deduplication logic—when both the full title and the `& Coriander` fragment are selected, the shorter substring gets prioritized and removes the longer version, leaving just a poor-scoring fragment that probably falls below the threshold. seems like the most plausible chain: \n1. Both \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" and \"& Coriander\" pass hard filters\n2. Both score above threshold  \n3. Deduplication removes the full join (it contains \"& Coriander\" as substring)\n4. \"& Coriander\" alone survives but... wait, the test says got '' not '& Coriander'\n\nHmm, unless \"& Coriander\" doesn't pass threshold. Or maybe \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" also passes threshold separately, and after deduplication the result is \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" which doesn't equal the expected... but the test says got ''.\n\nLet me focus on what I can actually observe: the title spans two lines with the continuation on line 2, the two-line join produces the correct full title, and the deduplication logic prefers shorter substrings, so \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" would eliminate the full join. Now let me trace through the dedup filter logic more carefully to see what's actually being removed. So the single line should survive the deduplication since nothing else contains it. But getting an empty string suggests the issue might be elsewhere—maybe in the scoring step where mixed-case titles don't generate strong embeddings, or there's a threshold problem when there are no ALL_CAPS candidates to fall back on. Let me trace through the scoring logic to see what's happening. The 0.08 threshold floor is indeed quite strict—if candidates don't naturally score well due to lack of ALL_CAPS formatting or too many short fragments, nothing makes it through and we get an empty result. For the Finnish flatbreads case, both the ALL_CAPS titles appear later in the file after messy OCR text at the start, so the algorithm is picking up the first one it encounters.\n\nThe multi-title guard logic is checking whether multiple candidates are selected...\n\nChecking the filtering logic...\n\nIf there are at least 2 all-caps titles, it keeps only those. If there's exactly 1 all-caps title, it picks the highest-scoring candidate overall. But I need to trace through what happens with the 2-line join \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS Maitorieska (Finland)\" — does it pass the all-caps check, and how does deduplication handle it against the individual titles?\n\nLooking at the actual file content, I'm seeing corrupted or garbled text at the beginning that doesn't match the expected recipe format. This might be affecting how the titles are being parsed and filtered. I'm tracing through the logic of how candidates are filtered and why \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" isn't making it into the final results. The algorithm skips short garbled lines, but longer ones like the first line pass through despite being corrupted OCR. Most candidates then fail the hard filters due to garbled text detection. The real issue seems to be in how the structural heading logic works—I need to figure out which candidate gets selected as the base heading and why the potato flatbreads title isn't being recognized as a valid structural heading. The prefix filter checks if \"DAT FLATBREADS\" is the structural heading and removes any candidates that would be its prefixes, though none seem