hat I can determine: \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" appears late in the document at line 29 out of 43, which is about 67% through. The position factor only boosts candidates in the first half of the document, so at that position it doesn't help—that's likely why \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" won out instead of the combined title. .0 (no boost).\n\nBut more importantly: the `candidate.position` is the line index in the original lines array (not nonEmptyLines). So line 29 out of 43 total lines = relative position 0.67. While \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" is at line 16/43 = 0.37, getting a position boost of 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - 0.37*2) = 1.0 + 0.12 * 0.26 = 1.031.\n\nIf both get similar embedding scores, \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" gets a small position boost. With threshold at best*0.7, if \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" barely fails the threshold...\n\nActually, I think the real problem is how the structural heading logic works with prefix matching. The code is looking for a candidate that starts with the base heading text followed by a special character, but \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" doesn't match that pattern since it starts with \"potato\" instead of \"milk\". So it won't be recognized as a structural variant of the base heading. breads \" is false, so it doesn't get filtered out. Let me check if there's a two-line version like \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS Maitorieska (Finland)\" that could be a candidate—but that's not in all caps, so it wouldn't be in the `allCapsSelected` list either. I'm looking at the actual file content now to see what might be causing the issue, and the text appears corrupted or malformed in the first few lines. I'm checking whether \"DAT FLATBREADS\" qualifies as a structural heading by examining if each significant word has at least 4 alphabetic characters—\"DAT\" only has 3, so it fails that requirement. Now I'm moving through the candidates in order to find the first actual structural heading that meets all the criteria.\n\n\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" works because all three significant words have at least 4 letters, so that becomes my base heading. I then look for any continuation of this heading in the candidates, but don't find one, so \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" is also my first structural heading.\n\nNow I'm applying the prefix removal filter...\n\nFiltering the selected candidates to remove any that start with the structural heading as a prefix. When I check \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" against \"finnish milk flatbreads\", it doesn't match the prefix pattern, so it survives the filter. Both headings should make it through to the multi-title guard check.\n\nNow I'm calculating the position factor for each candidate to see if that's affecting the final selection. \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" at line 16 gets a position factor of about 1.036, while \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" further down the file might be scoring lower due to its position. So the second title \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" scores 0.17, which falls just below the 0.196 threshold. The problem is clear now: the structural heading bonus applied to the first title inflates the best base score, which then raises the threshold through the 0.7 multiplier. This creates a barrier that subsequent titles without that bonus can't clear, even though they're legitimate recipe entries. It's a cascading effect where one title's bonus penalizes all the others on multi-recipe pages.\n\nThe code comment acknowledges trying to avoid position boost inflation, but the structural and ALL_CAPS bonuses are still baked into the base score calculation, causing the exact same problem.\n\nNow looking at the \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" case, the title spans two lines in the source with the continuation on the second line. The `firstStructuralHeading` logic was designed specifically to handle this kind of multi-line title scenario.\n\nTracing through the algorithm, line 29 contains \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" which is what got returned. This is all caps with multiple words, so it passes the structural heading check. The significant words filter is picking out the uppercase-heavy terms like \"FRON\", \"WHEAT\", and \"BUNS\". I'm checking that all the filtered words have at least 4 letters, which they do. The line \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" is being detected as a structural heading, though \"FRON\" is clearly a garbled OCR result from \"SAFFRON\". This heading appears at line 29, while the actual full recipe title \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" is further down at line 54, so the algorithm is using the truncated version as the base heading and now looking for continuation patterns.\n\nThe algorithm doesn't find a continuation for \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\", so it stays as the base heading. The problem is that this garbled heading gets bonus points for being all caps and structurally formatted, which inflates the score threshold and could exclude the correct title \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\". Meanwhile, the actual correct title spans two lines—\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" on line 54 and \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" on line 55—which should be joined together.\n\nNow I'm checking if the joined version passes the hard filters. It's 61 characters, which is fine, and it's not an ingredient or metadata. For the garbled check, I'm examining whether it has lowercase letters or sentence boundaries that would flag it as corrupted, but it's all uppercase with proper word boundaries, so it should pass. true. So this is an ALL_CAPS candidate that also qualifies as a structural heading since it has at least two words and passes the all-caps check. Now I'm filtering the words to find significant ones—those with more than one uppercase letter—which gives me \"SAFFRON\", \"WHEAT\", \"BUNS\", \"WITH\", \"QUARK\", \"COTTAGE\", \"CHEESE\", and \"(VARIATION\", while filtering out single-letter words like \"/\" and \"D)\".\n\nAll these significant